An upper bound search starts from a known feasible cycle time and tries to reduce it iteratively. A common strategy is to reduce it successively by one and to try to find a better feasible solution by some heuristic algorithm. However, it is well known that heuristic assignment procedures are not monotone, i.e., they may find a feasible solution for some cycle time but not for larger cycle times. To overcome this, we propose to modify the upper bound search to examine an interval of cycle times ending at the current best upper bound. If the current lower and upper
