bounds on the cycle time are C and C, the upper bound search will try to find a feasible solution for all cycle times between max{C, ⌊ pC ⌋
} and C − 1 for a given factor p ∈ (0,1) and update C to the best cycle time found, if any. Otherwise, the upper bound search continues with the same interval. Since the beam search is probabilistic this may produce a feasible solution in a later trial. The interval search depends on three parameters: the minimum search time tmin, the maximum search time tmax and the maximum number of repetitions r. The search terminates if the cycle time found equals the lower bound, or if the maximum time or the maximum number of repetitions are exceeded, but not before the minimum search time has passed.
Initially, the value of C is set to the best of all lower bounds presented in Section 3. The initial upper bound C is determined by an single run of the beam search with a beam factor of one.
